Scottish independent schools improved academic achievement records, without going down in 2018 as well, and once again demonstrated exceptional exam results that were only further enhanced by individual and collective achievements in sports, art, music and other community merit.
When a total of more than 30,000 pupils are enrolled across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide their students and their parents with the highest level of service possible.
Independent schools seek to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and to be citizens of the world.
Working in the education sector, which can create and implement the intended school program, we can see that modern languages continue to be popular and are chosen willingly in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you can talk to a person in a language he understands, he will understand you with his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will speak to his heart."
It is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
According to the results of this year's recent examinations, we can say that languages excel at the peak of popularity and have the best retention ratings in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language students received the highest A rating.
Data collected from 74 schools that are members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of pupils received the highest rating of A during the Mandarin language exam, the highest rating of A was given to 72 percent of those who studied German, as well as the highest rating of A was given to 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland consider foreign language proficiency an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as an elective are now considered as important as basic subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that of all the reasons employers found it difficult to fill jobs, 17 percent had insufficient language skills.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming mandatory to prepare young people for their future careers.
As access to employment will depend heavily on languages in the future, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses, learning a second language will make him significantly superior to others in the future if he has these lifelong skills needed.
By being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who knows several languages will be much more competitive.
According to a poll conducted by YouGov in 2013 involving more than 4,000 UK adults, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to participate in the conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, 15 percent.
