North Korea says it will not disarm unilaterally in any way, unable to trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepen their distrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would certainly not unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho's global organizations told the General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant goodwill measures" in recent years, such as halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test base, and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we have not received a similar response from the U.S. side," he lamented.
"Without any confidence in the U.S., we will not be able to trust our national security, and under such circumstances we will by no means be the first to disarm unilaterally."
While Ri repeated North Korea's already heard complaints about Washington's opposition to the phased approach to nuclear disarmament, which would reward North Korea by taking steps in stages, his statement stood out by the fact that he had not completely ruled out the idea of bilateral disarmament, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first meeting of the U.S. President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on "disarming the Korean peninsula", and Trump promised to ensure North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also refuses to relax tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. demands nuclear disarmament first and increases pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal through coercive methods, even abandoning the declaration of an end to the war," Ri said.
"To think that sanctions can bring us back is like pursuing utopian dreams for people we don't care about.
But the problem is that continuing sanctions deepen our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which was highlighted by the U.S. leader at the United Nations just earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months: "If another country were South Korea on this nuclear disarmament issue rather than the United States, the issue of nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have come to such a stalemate."
However, Ri's tone of speech changed dramatically compared to last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that when "Mr. President of Evil" Trump called Kim a "missile gentleman" preparing a suicide mission, targeting North Korean missiles at the United States was absolutely inevitable.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, boasted to Kim for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said that there was still much work to be done and that sanctions must remain until North Korea met its nuclear disarmament requirements.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not scheduled a timeline for this, and said that "if it takes two years, three years, or five months to do so, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia said the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
