North Korea promised during a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle the missile base and nuclear complex if the United States took "appropriate measures".
According to him, Kim said that the "appropriate measures" he was pursuing were the security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore and a move to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn enough to rest
A new course at Harvard University this year encouraged all of its students to sleep more in order to combat the growing culture of the match in the studios by consuming caffeine and not sleeping at night.
One academic found that in the best university in the world, students often do not even have basic knowledge of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and Brigam City, a specialist in Women's Hospitals, has prepared a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for preparing this course visited him after talking about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why am I only being told about it now, in the final year of my studies?'
She said no one had told her about the importance of sleep, and that surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course is offered for the first time this year. It explains to students how the most important quality sleep habits help to achieve academic and sporting results, and improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services department, said the university decided to offer this course when it became clear that students were severely short of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
One section contains a dormitory room photo where students can click on coffee mugs, curtains, trainers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine, light, how sleep deprivation affects sports performance and how important walking to sleep routines is.
In the next section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the student campus with interactive icons that encourage participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We understand that this will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about health consequences when you choose to smoke," explained Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in not sleeping overnight, according to him, still exists. Modern technology and increasing pressure on students have led to the growing problem of sleep deprivation.
"Ensuring that enough and quality sleep should be the students' secret weapon in combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety," he said, "even avoiding gaining weight because lack of sleep turns the brain into a fasting regime, so students are constantly feeling hungry."
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course when he attended one of his taught courses last year, his first years at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to ask for a course available to the entire student campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to invite all postgraduate students to listen to this course before beginning to attend this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm clock when it is time to go to sleep, just like lifting, and beware of the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic devices and LED lighting as they can knock your circadian rhythm out of balance, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
