HIV/AIDS: China reports increase in new cases of disease 14%
China reports a 14% increase in the number of citizens infected with HIV and AIDS.
According to representatives of health authorities, more than 820,000 people have been infected with the infection in the country.
40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018 alone.
Most newly infected people have had the infection transmitted sexually, and this is different from past statistics.
Traditionally, HIV infection has spread rapidly in parts of China due to infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people infected with HIV has thus dropped to almost zero , according to representatives of Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan province.
Over time, however, the number of people living with HIV infection and AIDS in China has risen to 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a sensitive issue in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China as early as 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is common.
Because conservative values prevail in the country, 70-90% of men who have sexual relations with men end up marrying women.
Most cases of infection with the disease occur due to improper protective measures during such sexual relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as one way to combat the problem.
