National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
The new study, conducted at a Scottish highland estate, aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The findings are expected to provide new insights into the behaviour of unique flying mammals and provide some guidance for future conservation activities.
Scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will observe asses dwarves, sopranos, brown earls and water mice in the gardens of Wester Ross Inverev in their study.
Special recorders will be arranged in certain areas of the area to track the activity of bats throughout the season.
National Health Service personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys with hand-held detectors.
Expert analysis of all audio recordings will determine the frequency of signals emitted by bats and the activity of one or another type.
A map of habitable habitats and a report will then be created to help shape a detailed picture of behaviour on a landscape-wide scale.
Rob Dewar, Conservation Advisor for the National Trust for Scotland (NTS), hopes the results will reveal which habitat is most important to bats and how each species uses it.
This information will help determine the benefits of residential habitat maintenance such as grassland creation, as well as finding out how best to care for woodland to make it suitable for bats and other related species.
In the last century, bat populations have declined in Scotland and across the UK.
They are threatened by construction and real estate development work affecting hatcheries and destroying residential areas.
Wind farms and lightning are also a threat, as are flycatchers, some of the chemicals used in the treatment of building materials, as well as hunting domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, catching prey during night hunting is more aided by the ears than the eyes.
Bats pinpoint the location of insects or obstacles in the flight path by an elaborate echolocation.
The NTS, which is responsible for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, looks extremely responsibly at bats.
There are ten trained experts who conduct surveys, hatchery inspections and sometimes rescue operations on a regular basis .
The organization even created the first and only reserve specifically for bats in Scotland in Damfries and the Threeve Manor in Galloway, where eight out of ten species of Scottish bats live.
Manor keeper David Thompson says the estate area is ideal for them.
"We have a great place at Threeve Manor for bats," he said.
We have old buildings, lots of mature trees and great areas to live in.
But we don't know much about bats yet, so working here and in other places will help you better understand what they need in order to thrive."
He stresses that it is crucial to check for bats before starting maintenance work on the site, as inadvertent destruction of one hatchery could kill up to 400 females and young, which could lead to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected and are prohibited from being killed, teased or disturbed, and their hatchery is also prohibited from being destroyed.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Bat Conservation Fund, urged the public to contribute to the rescue of the bats.
She stated, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we don't even know how many indigenous species are doing."
