"Red Flood" news: Concentration declines in Painelas, Manati and Sarasota
According to a recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission (FWC), the total concentration of "red tide" in the Tampa Bay area is decreasing.
According to the FWC, more fragmentary blooms have been observed in the counties of Painelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier, suggesting a decline in concentration.
The flowering of the "Red Flood" spans approximately 130 miles of coastline from northern Painelas to southern Lee Counties.
Flowering areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast in Hillsboro County, but fewer than last week .
"Red Flooding" has also been observed in Pasco County.
Last week, concentrations in and along Painelas County were reported to be average, along the Hillsboro County coast from low to high, in Manati County from background to high, in Sarasota County and along the coast from background to high, in Charlotte County from background to medium, along the Li County coast from background to high, and in Collie County from low.
Cases of respiratory irritation are still reported in Painelas, Manati, Sarasota, Li, and Collier Counties.
There have been no reports of airway irritation in northwestern Florida in the past week.
